                id: 110,
                title: "The Food Truck Dream (J)",
                text: "Fourteen-year-old Carlos had always loved cooking with his grandmother. She taught him to make traditional Mexican dishes like tamales, pozole, and her famous street tacos. When his family faced financial troubles, Carlos had an idea that seemed crazy at first. What if they started a food truck selling abuela's recipes? His parents were skeptical. Running a food business required permits, equipment, and startup money they did not have. But Carlos had learned about business plans in his economics class. He stayed up late researching and created a detailed proposal. He calculated costs, projected earnings, and identified a perfect location near the local college. His grandmother was touched that Carlos wanted to share her recipes with the world. She agreed to help, but only if Carlos kept his grades up. His father used savings to buy an old van that needed work. The whole family spent weekends fixing it up and converting it into a food truck. Opening day was terrifying. Would anyone come? Would they like the food? By noon, a line stretched down the block. Students and professors raved about the authentic flavors. Social media posts brought even more customers. The food truck became so successful that it helped pay off family debts. Carlos learned to balance school, work, and family responsibilities. His grandmother's recipes brought the community together. People from different backgrounds connected over shared meals. Carlos realized that honoring his heritage could also build his future. Now he dreams of opening a restaurant someday, with his grandmother's photo on the wall.",
