                id: 113,
                title: "The Psychology of Gaming (J)",
                text: "Have you ever wondered why video games are so hard to put down? Game designers use psychology to make their games engaging, and understanding their tricks can help you play smarter. One technique is called variable rewards. Instead of giving you a prize every time, games reward you randomly. This unpredictability keeps you playing because you never know when the next reward is coming. Slot machines use the same strategy. That is why loot boxes and random drops are so common in modern games. Another technique is the progress bar. Seeing that you are ninety percent of the way to the next level creates a strong urge to finish. Game designers place these progress indicators everywhere to keep you engaged. The sunk cost fallacy also plays a role. When you have invested hours into a game, quitting feels like wasting all that time. So you keep playing even when you are not having fun anymore. Games also use social pressure. Multiplayer games create communities where you feel obligated to play with friends. Missing out on limited-time events triggers fear that you will fall behind. Knowing these techniques does not mean you have to stop gaming. It means you can make conscious choices about how and when you play. Set timers to remind yourself to take breaks. Recognize when you are playing because you genuinely enjoy it versus when you are just chasing rewards. Video games can be great entertainment and even teach valuable skills. The key is playing with awareness rather than letting the game control you.",
