                text: "When the empty lot on Maple Street became filled with trash and weeds, thirteen-year-old Aisha decided to do something about it. She had learned about community gardens in her social studies class and thought one could transform her neighborhood. Aisha started by researching what it would take. She needed permission from the city, supplies for gardening, and volunteers to help. It seemed overwhelming, but she took it one step at a time. First, she wrote a letter to the city council explaining her idea. To her surprise, they approved it within a month. Next, Aisha created flyers and went door to door asking neighbors to help. Some people were skeptical, but many were excited. A retired teacher offered to donate seeds. A construction worker volunteered to build raised garden beds. Local businesses contributed soil and tools. The first workday brought out thirty volunteers. Together, they cleared trash, pulled weeds, and built twelve garden beds. Aisha organized teams so everyone had a job. Children painted signs while adults did heavy lifting. Over the following months, the garden flourished. Tomatoes, peppers, beans, and flowers grew where garbage had been. Neighbors who had never spoken began talking while they gardened together. The empty lot became a gathering place for the community. A local news station did a story about the garden, calling Aisha a young leader. She felt proud, but what mattered most was seeing her neighbors working together.",
