                title: "Code Breakers (L)",
                text: "The national cybersecurity competition attracted the best young programmers from across the country. Sixteen-year-old Dev had qualified as part of a four-person team from his high school, and now they faced challenges that tested everything they had learned about computer security. The competition simulated real-world scenarios. Teams had to defend their own computer systems while trying to find vulnerabilities in opponents' systems. Points were earned by protecting your data and by ethically exposing weaknesses in other teams' defenses. It was like a digital game of capture the flag, but with serious implications for future careers. Dev's team struggled in the first round. They had spent too much time building offensive tools and not enough on defense. Other teams exploited holes in their security while they scrambled to patch problems. By lunch, they were in last place. During the break, Dev called a team meeting. They needed to change strategy. Instead of trying to do everything, they would specialize. Maya would focus entirely on defense. Raj would handle network monitoring. Priya would analyze opponent patterns. Dev would coordinate and make strategic decisions. The new approach worked. Maya built defenses so strong that no team could penetrate them for the rest of the competition. Meanwhile, Raj noticed patterns in network traffic that revealed when opponents were planning attacks. Priya's analysis helped them identify the weakest points in other teams' systems. In the final hour, they executed a perfectly timed strategy. While other teams attacked each other, Dev's team quietly accumulated points through superior defense and precise, surgical strikes at vulnerable targets. They did not win first place, but they climbed from last to fourth. More importantly, they demonstrated something the judges valued highly: the ability to adapt, collaborate, and learn from failure.",
