                text: "When Ahmad arrived in America from Syria, he felt completely lost. He did not speak English well, did not understand American culture, and missed his home desperately. Everything had been taken from him by war: his house, his school, his friends, his sense of belonging. The only thing that remained was his love of soccer. A local community center started a soccer program for refugee children. Players came from Syria, Somalia, Myanmar, Guatemala, and other countries. They spoke different languages and had different customs, but they all understood the universal language of the beautiful game. Coach Martinez, herself an immigrant from Mexico, knew that soccer could do more than just provide exercise. She used the sport to build connections between children who had experienced trauma and displacement. On the field, backgrounds did not matter. Only teamwork, effort, and respect counted. Ahmad slowly began to open up. He made friends with Fatima from Somalia, who played midfielder with incredible endurance. He learned hand signals to communicate with Juan from Guatemala, whose Spanish was as limited as Ahmad's English. Together, they developed plays that worked without needing words. The team entered a local youth league. Other teams had been playing together for years and had professional coaching. The refugee team lost their first several games badly. But they kept improving, kept learning, kept supporting each other through every defeat. By the end of the season, they had won enough games to make the playoffs. In the semifinal match, they faced the league's best team. The game went to overtime, then penalty kicks. Ahmad took the final shot. When the ball hit the back of the net, his teammates mobbed him in celebration. Crying with joy, Ahmad realized he had found something he thought war had stolen forever. He had found a team, a community, a place where he belonged.",
