                title: "The Invention That Changed Everything (L)",
                text: "Thirteen-year-old Kenji had always been a tinkerer, taking apart electronics to see how they worked and building strange contraptions in his garage. His parents worried he was wasting time on silly projects. But Kenji was about to prove that his curious mind could create something truly valuable. It started with his grandmother's arthritis. Her hands hurt so badly some days that she could not open jars, button her shirt, or hold a book. Kenji watched her struggle and wondered if he could help. He researched assistive technology and found that many devices were either too expensive or too complicated for elderly people to use. Kenji decided to build something better. He spent months prototyping a simple, affordable device that could help people with limited hand strength grip and twist objects. Using a 3D printer at his school's maker space, he created handle attachments that could fit on jars, doorknobs, and other everyday items. His grandmother was his first test user. Her feedback helped him improve the design repeatedly. The grip needed to be softer. The mechanism needed to be simpler. Each version got better based on real-world use. A teacher encouraged Kenji to enter a young inventors competition. He almost did not submit his entry, thinking his simple device was not impressive enough compared to robots and apps. But the judges saw something special. His invention solved a real problem for real people. It was affordable to produce and easy to use. Kenji won second place and received funding to develop his invention further. A medical supply company expressed interest in manufacturing his design. More important than any prize, Kenji's grandmother could now open jars by herself for the first time in years. Seeing her independence restored taught Kenji that the best inventions are not always the most complicated.",
