                title: "Climate Change and Extreme Weather (L)",
                text: "In recent years, news reports about extreme weather have become increasingly common. Record-breaking heat waves, devastating hurricanes, historic floods, and unprecedented wildfires seem to occur more frequently than ever before. Scientists have confirmed that climate change is making many types of extreme weather more likely and more intense. Earth's climate has always varied naturally over thousands of years. However, since the Industrial Revolution, human activities have rapidly increased greenhouse gases in the atmosphere. Burning fossil fuels for energy releases carbon dioxide, which traps heat like a blanket around the planet. Global average temperatures have risen about two degrees Fahrenheit since 1900, with most of that increase happening in recent decades. This might not sound like much, but small changes in average temperature have big effects on weather patterns. Warmer air holds more water vapor, which leads to heavier rainfall and more severe flooding in some areas. At the same time, increased evaporation creates worse droughts in other regions. Warmer ocean waters provide more energy to hurricanes, making them stronger. Heat waves last longer and reach higher temperatures than before. Each fraction of a degree of warming increases risks of extreme events. The effects are not distributed equally around the world. Some communities face multiple threats while having fewer resources to adapt. Coastal cities must deal with rising sea levels and stronger storms. Agricultural regions face changing growing seasons and water shortages. People living in poverty often suffer most because they cannot afford to move or rebuild after disasters. Scientists say that reducing greenhouse gas emissions can slow future warming and limit extreme weather increases. Transitioning to renewable energy, improving efficiency, and protecting forests all help. Individual choices matter, but larger systemic changes are essential.",
