                text: "Your body is home to trillions of tiny organisms that you cannot see without a microscope. Bacteria, viruses, fungi, and other microbes live on your skin, in your mouth, and especially in your digestive system. Together, these microscopic residents are called your microbiome, and scientists are discovering they play crucial roles in your health. The idea of bacteria living inside you might sound gross or scary. For a long time, scientists thought all bacteria were harmful germs that caused disease. We now know that most bacteria in your body are either harmless or actively helpful. Some help digest food and produce vitamins. Others train your immune system to recognize and fight actual threats. Your gut microbiome is particularly important. The bacteria in your intestines help break down complex foods that your body cannot digest on its own. They produce chemicals that affect your mood and brain function. Research suggests connections between gut bacteria and conditions ranging from obesity to depression to autoimmune diseases. Every person has a unique microbiome, shaped by factors including genetics, diet, environment, and early life experiences. Babies born naturally acquire their first bacteria from their mothers during birth. Breast milk contains sugars specifically designed to feed beneficial gut bacteria. Throughout life, what you eat continues to shape your microbial community. A diet rich in fiber and fermented foods promotes diverse, healthy bacteria. Processed foods and excessive antibiotics can harm beneficial microbes. Taking antibiotics when you are sick kills harmful bacteria but also destroys good ones, which is why doctors increasingly prescribe them carefully. Scientists are exploring ways to manipulate the microbiome to treat diseases. Understanding your microbiome reveals that human health depends on cooperation between your body and its microscopic inhabitants.",
