                text: "Maya had spent three years developing her artistic style. She practiced drawing for hours every day, studied color theory, and learned digital illustration software. Her portfolio of fantasy landscapes had earned her recognition in online art communities. When she was accepted to a prestigious summer arts program, she felt her hard work had finally paid off. Then everything changed. A new AI art generator appeared online, capable of creating stunning images from simple text descriptions. Within weeks, social media flooded with AI-generated artwork. Some images were beautiful. Many mimicked styles of human artists whose work had been used to train the AI without permission. Maya was horrified to discover AI-generated images that looked remarkably similar to her style. The algorithm had apparently learned from her posted artwork. Now anyone could type a few words and produce images that resembled what she had spent years learning to create. Some of her followers began sharing AI art instead of supporting human artists. Commissions dried up as potential clients realized they could get similar results for free. Maya felt like her skills had become worthless overnight. She considered giving up art entirely. Her mentor at the summer program offered a different perspective. Technology had disrupted art before, she explained. Photography once threatened painters who specialized in realistic portraits. Digital tools worried artists who worked in traditional media. Each time, human creativity found new ways to express itself. The mentor encouraged Maya to focus on what AI could not replicate: emotional storytelling, personal vision, and the human experience behind art. Maya began creating pieces that combined her technical skills with deeply personal narratives about her immigrant family's history. She included imperfections and quirks that made her work distinctly human. She connected with audiences who valued knowing an artist's story and intention.",
