                title: "The Wilderness Rescue (M)",
                text: "The helicopter crash left fourteen-year-old Jordan and her father stranded in the Alaskan wilderness with minimal supplies. They had been flying to a remote fishing camp when engine failure forced an emergency landing in dense forest. Her father's leg was badly injured, leaving Jordan responsible for their survival until rescue arrived. Jordan assessed their situation carefully, trying to remain calm despite her terror. They had a small first aid kit, emergency blankets, a knife, some energy bars, and a satellite phone with a cracked screen that might or might not work. The pilot's emergency beacon was damaged in the crash. They were completely alone. Her first priority was shelter. Using techniques she had learned in wilderness survival videos, Jordan constructed a lean-to from fallen branches and pine boughs. It would not be comfortable, but it would protect them from wind and rain. She helped her father crawl inside and elevated his injured leg to reduce swelling. Water came next. Jordan found a small stream about a hundred yards from their shelter. Without a container, she improvised, using large leaves to carry small amounts back to her father. She knew untreated water could make them sick, but dehydration was an immediate threat. The satellite phone showed one bar of signal when she climbed to higher ground. Her message was brief but clear: their location, her father's injury, their supplies. She had no way to know if it went through. Days passed slowly. Jordan rationed their food carefully and foraged for edible plants she recognized from survival guides. She kept a signal fire burning during the day, adding green branches to create smoke visible from the air. On the fourth day, Jordan heard the distant sound of helicopter rotors. She scrambled to add more branches to her signal fire. When the rescue helicopter appeared over the treeline, she waved frantically. Paramedics reached them within the hour.",
