                title: "The Debate Tournament (M)",
                text: "Aaliyah had joined the debate team to overcome her fear of public speaking. She never expected to make it to the state championship, let alone face the topic that would challenge everything she believed. The resolution they would debate asked whether social media companies should be held legally responsible for harmful content posted by users. Aaliyah had strong personal opinions on the issue. Her younger brother had been cyberbullied so severely that he had to change schools. She blamed the platforms that allowed harassment to spread. She was assigned to argue the negative side, defending social media companies against legal responsibility. Her coach explained that debating positions you disagree with develops critical thinking and empathy. Understanding opposing arguments makes you more persuasive. Still, it felt wrong. Aaliyah threw herself into research. She learned about Section 230, the law that protects internet platforms from liability for user content. She discovered arguments about free speech, innovation, and the practical impossibility of moderating billions of posts. She interviewed a lawyer who explained how making platforms responsible for everything could destroy the internet as we knew it. Slowly, her perspective became more nuanced. The issue was more complicated than she had realized. Holding platforms liable might reduce harmful content, but it could also lead to excessive censorship that silenced legitimate speech. Small websites could not afford the legal risk, leaving only giant corporations. The championship debate was intense. Aaliyah faced a talented opponent who argued passionately for platform responsibility. She responded with careful reasoning, acknowledging the real harms while explaining unintended consequences. The judges asked challenging questions that pushed both debaters to defend their positions. Aaliyah's team won by a narrow margin. But the victory felt less important than what she had learned. Complex problems rarely have simple solutions. People on both sides of difficult issues often have valid concerns.",
