                text: "Fourteen-year-old Marcus discovered music production software on his older sister's laptop. Within a year, he was creating beats in his bedroom that sounded as professional as anything on the radio. When one of his instrumentals went viral on social media, he suddenly found himself with an opportunity he never expected: a real artist wanted to use his music. The rapper who reached out, a rising star named Velocity, offered Marcus five hundred dollars for exclusive rights to one of his beats. To Marcus, this seemed like an incredible amount of money. He had never made a penny from his hobby before. His parents were proud but cautioned him to be careful. Marcus did some research and discovered that five hundred dollars was far below industry standard for beats. Hit songs could generate millions in royalties. Selling exclusive rights meant giving up any future earnings, no matter how successful the song became. He faced a difficult decision. The money was guaranteed, and Velocity might help launch his career by crediting him as the producer. But if he undersold his work, he might regret it forever. He also learned that the music industry often exploited young creators who did not understand their value. Marcus negotiated. Instead of selling exclusive rights, he proposed a licensing agreement that would give Velocity permission to use the beat while Marcus retained ownership. He would receive a smaller upfront payment but would earn royalties if the song made money. His research had taught him what was fair. Velocity almost walked away but eventually agreed to the deal. Six months later, the song hit streaming charts. Marcus began receiving royalty checks that added up to far more than the original offer. More importantly, other artists started reaching out, interested in working with him. The experience taught Marcus crucial lessons about valuing his creative work and protecting his interests in business negotiations.",
