                id: 135,
                title: "The Dark Side of Fast Fashion (M)",
                text: "That trendy shirt selling for ten dollars at your favorite store might seem like a great deal. But understanding the true cost of fast fashion reveals troubling consequences for workers, communities, and the environment. The cheap clothing that fills our closets comes with a price that is not on the tag. Fast fashion refers to inexpensive clothing produced rapidly to follow the latest trends. Companies like Zara, H&M, and Shein release new styles weekly, encouraging consumers to constantly buy more. Americans now purchase five times as much clothing as they did in 1980. Most of these garments end up in landfills within a year. The environmental impact is staggering. The fashion industry is responsible for about ten percent of global carbon emissions, more than international flights and shipping combined. It is the second-largest consumer of water worldwide. A single cotton shirt requires about 700 gallons of water to produce. Synthetic fabrics shed microplastics that pollute oceans and enter the food chain. Dyeing and treating fabrics releases toxic chemicals into waterways, particularly in developing countries with weak environmental regulations. Behind the low prices are workers, often women and children, laboring in dangerous conditions for poverty wages. The 2013 collapse of the Rana Plaza factory in Bangladesh killed over a thousand garment workers and exposed the dark reality of global supply chains. Workers regularly face long hours, unsafe buildings, and wages that cannot cover basic needs. When consumers demand cheaper clothes, brands pressure factories to cut costs, and workers pay the price. What can individuals do? Buying fewer, higher-quality garments that last longer reduces environmental impact. Shopping secondhand keeps clothes out of landfills and reduces demand for new production. Supporting brands that treat workers fairly and use sustainable practices creates market pressure for change.",
