                text: "Dr. Sarah Chen had studied the Mendenhall Glacier for thirty years. She had watched it retreat, year after year, its ancient ice melting into the sea. Now, standing at its shrinking edge with her daughter Maya, she struggled to find words for what they were witnessing. Maya, fifteen years old and passionate about environmental science, had begged to accompany her mother on this research expedition. She had grown up seeing photographs of the glacier taken decades apart, watching the ice slowly disappear. But nothing had prepared her for seeing it in person. The ice that remained was stunning, blue and ancient, carved by forces that operated over thousands of years. Yet it was also clearly dying. Waterfalls of meltwater cascaded from its surface. Chunks of ice calved off with thunderous crashes. The glacier that her mother had first visited as a young researcher was now a fraction of its former size. Sarah explained the science while they collected data. Rising global temperatures were accelerating melt rates. The albedo effect meant that as white ice disappeared, darker rock and water absorbed more heat, speeding the process further. Feedback loops were pushing the system toward a tipping point from which recovery might be impossible. The data they gathered would contribute to climate models, but Sarah harbored private doubts about whether it would make a difference. She had spent her career sounding alarms that too few people heeded. Sometimes the weight of knowing felt unbearable. Maya saw her mother's sadness and felt something different: determination. Her generation would live with the consequences of decisions made before they were born. They would face sea level rise, climate refugees, ecosystem collapse. But they would also have opportunities to innovate, adapt, and perhaps prevent the worst outcomes. She refused to accept despair. On their last evening at the glacier, mother and daughter sat together watching the sunset paint the ice in shades of pink and gold.",
