                text: "Seventeen-year-old James discovered the fraud by accident. Working a summer internship at his uncle's pharmaceutical company, he was organizing old files when he found documents showing that the company had hidden negative results from drug trials. The medication they sold to millions of people might be less effective and more dangerous than the public knew. At first, James thought he must be misunderstanding something. His uncle was a respected businessman who talked about helping patients. The company employed hundreds of people in their community. Surely there was an explanation that did not involve deliberate deception. But the more documents James examined, the clearer the picture became. Executives had known about problems for years and chosen to suppress the information to protect profits. James faced an impossible choice. Reporting what he found would devastate his family. His uncle would likely go to prison. His cousins would lose their father. His own mother, who worked at the company, might lose her job. The entire community depended on the company's success. People who had known James his whole life would see him as a traitor. But staying silent meant being complicit in harm to patients who trusted the medication. People might be getting sick or dying because the company prioritized money over honesty. How could he live with himself knowing what he knew and doing nothing? James sought guidance from a teacher he trusted, being careful not to reveal specific details. She helped him think through his options and values without telling him what to do. She also connected him with a lawyer who specialized in whistleblower cases and could explain his legal protections. The decision took weeks of agonizing reflection. James ultimately chose to report the fraud to regulators, using channels that protected his identity initially. When his involvement eventually became known, the fallout was everything he had feared. But he had stayed true to his conscience.",
