                id: 145,
                title: "Ocean Plastic: A Global Crisis (N)",
                text: "Every year, millions of tons of plastic waste enter the world's oceans. This pollution, accumulating in garbage patches and washing up on beaches from the Arctic to Antarctica, represents one of the most visible environmental crises of our time. Understanding where ocean plastic comes from, what harm it causes, and what can be done about it is essential for addressing this growing problem. Plastic production has exploded since the 1950s, when synthetic materials became cheap and widely available. The convenience of single-use plastics transformed consumer culture: plastic bags, bottles, packaging, and countless other items became part of daily life. But plastic does not biodegrade like natural materials. Instead, it breaks down into smaller and smaller pieces over hundreds of years, persisting in the environment long after its useful life ends. Most ocean plastic comes from land-based sources. Inadequate waste management in coastal areas allows trash to wash into rivers that carry it to the sea. The countries responsible for the most ocean plastic pollution are often developing nations with rapidly growing consumption but limited infrastructure for managing waste. However, wealthy countries contribute too, both through their own waste and through exporting recyclables that end up in poorly managed facilities overseas. The harm from plastic pollution takes many forms. Large debris entangles marine animals, causing injury and death. Sea turtles mistake plastic bags for jellyfish and starve with stomachs full of indigestible material. Seabirds feed plastic to their chicks. Microplastics, tiny fragments less than five millimeters across, have been found in every part of the ocean ecosystem, from surface waters to the deepest trenches, from plankton to whales. These particles enter the food chain with consequences we are only beginning to understand. Solutions require action at multiple levels. Reducing plastic production addresses the problem at its source. Improving waste management prevents existing plastic from reaching the ocean.",
