                title: "How Video Games Are Made (O)",
                text: "Behind every video game lies years of work by hundreds of creative professionals. Game development combines art, programming, storytelling, and psychology into interactive experiences. Understanding how games are made reveals why some become legendary while others are quickly forgotten. Every game begins with a concept phase. Designers ask fundamental questions: What makes this game fun? What emotions should players feel? Teams create detailed design documents describing every element. Next comes prototyping. Programmers build simple versions to test core mechanics. Does jumping feel responsive? Is difficulty balanced? Many games are abandoned at this stage when testing reveals problems. Games that survive move to full production. Artists create characters, environments, and visual effects. Writers develop dialogue and story. Programmers code thousands of systems‚Äîphysics, artificial intelligence, networking. Sound designers craft music that enhances emotional impact. Quality assurance testers play repeatedly, searching for bugs. A typical major game might have over 10,000 bugs requiring fixes before release. Finally, marketing teams build anticipation through trailers. After three to five years of development, the game launches‚Äîand players experience in hours what took thousands of people years to create.",
