                text: "Nature's most violent phenomena can destroy entire cities in hours. Understanding hurricanes, tornadoes, and tsunamis helps communities prepare for these devastating events. Each disaster type requires different survival strategies. Hurricanes are massive rotating storm systems forming over warm ocean waters. They can span 500 miles wide and last for weeks. The eye‚Äîa calm center surrounded by violent winds‚Äîcan create false safety. Hurricane Katrina in 2005 killed over 1,800 people and caused $125 billion in damage. Modern satellite tracking gives communities days of warning. Tornadoes are tightly spinning air columns descending from thunderstorms. Unlike hurricanes, they form rapidly and unpredictably. The most powerful tornadoes generate winds exceeding 300 miles per hour‚Äîstrong enough to lift houses from foundations. Underground shelters provide best protection. Tsunamis differ because they originate from underwater earthquakes or volcanic eruptions. Waves travel across oceans at jet speed, appearing small in deep water but growing into devastating walls near coastlines. The 2004 Indian Ocean tsunami killed approximately 230,000 people across fourteen countries. Warning systems now monitor seismic activity to alert coastal populations. Climate change is intensifying extreme weather events.",
