                title: "When Stars Die: Black Holes (P)",
                text: "Black holes are among the universe's most mysterious objects. These cosmic entities are so dense that nothing‚Äînot even light‚Äîcan escape their gravitational pull once it crosses a boundary called the event horizon. Understanding black holes helps scientists comprehend the universe's most extreme conditions. Black holes form when massive stars exhaust their nuclear fuel. Without energy pushing outward against gravity, the star collapses catastrophically. If the original star was large enough‚Äîabout twenty times our sun's mass‚Äîthis collapse creates a black hole. The dying star essentially falls into itself, compressing matter into an unimaginably small point called a singularity. Despite their name, black holes aren't empty space. They contain enormous mass concentrated in tiny volumes. Scientists can't see black holes directly but detect them through their effects. Material falling toward a black hole heats up and emits X-rays. Stars orbiting invisible companions reveal black holes through unusual movements. In 2019, the Event Horizon Telescope captured the first image of a black hole's shadow‚Äîa historic achievement requiring a planet-sized array of radio telescopes. Supermassive black holes, millions or billions of times our sun's mass, lurk at galaxy centers. Our Milky Way hosts one called Sagittarius A*, approximately four million solar masses.",
