                text: "Modern prosthetic limbs have transformed from simple wooden pegs into sophisticated devices that can respond to thought. This revolution in medical technology offers hope to millions who have lost limbs through accidents, illness, or birth differences. Traditional prosthetics were passive‚Äîartificial legs that allowed walking but couldn't adapt to terrain, or arms that could hold objects but not grip them firmly. Today's advanced prosthetics incorporate sensors, microprocessors, and motors. Computerized knees analyze walking patterns and automatically adjust for stairs, slopes, or uneven ground. Robotic hands contain multiple motors allowing individual finger movement. The most remarkable advancement involves connecting prosthetics directly to the nervous system. Targeted muscle reinnervation surgery redirects nerves that once controlled a missing limb to remaining muscles. Sensors detect electrical signals from these muscles, translating intentions into prosthetic movement. Users describe the experience as thinking about moving their artificial hand and watching it respond. Some experimental prosthetics even provide sensory feedback. Pressure sensors in artificial fingertips send signals to the brain, allowing users to feel objects they touch. Cost remains a significant barrier. Advanced prosthetics can exceed $100,000, and insurance coverage varies widely. Organizations worldwide work to provide prosthetics to those who cannot afford them.",
