                text: "In 79 CE, Mount Vesuvius erupted with catastrophic fury, burying the Roman city of Pompeii under twenty feet of volcanic ash. This tragedy preserved an ancient city so completely that archaeologists can reconstruct daily Roman life in remarkable detail. Approximately twenty thousand people lived in Pompeii when disaster struck. Warning signs‚Äîearthquakes and steam venting‚Äîwere ignored or misinterpreted. When Vesuvius finally exploded, it released thermal energy equivalent to thousands of nuclear bombs. Superheated gas and ash clouds called pyroclastic flows raced down the mountain at hundreds of miles per hour. Most victims died from thermal shock. The same ash that killed also preserved. Buildings, artwork, food, and personal objects remained intact beneath the volcanic debris. Excavations beginning in 1748 revealed streets, homes, shops, and public buildings. Frescoes‚Äîpaintings on wet plaster‚Äîmaintained their vivid colors. Loaves of bread remained in ovens. Graffiti on walls recorded ancient conversations and advertisements. Perhaps most poignant are the human remains. When bodies decomposed, they left hollow spaces in hardened ash. Archaeologists pour plaster into these cavities, creating casts capturing victims' final moments. Ongoing excavations continue revealing secrets about daily life in ancient Rome.",
