                text: "Autonomous vehicles promise to revolutionize transportation, potentially reducing accidents, emissions, and the stress of commuting. Yet fully self-driving cars remain perpetually 'just a few years away.' Understanding both the technological challenges and ethical dilemmas reveals why this revolution proceeds slower than promised. Self-driving cars perceive their environment through cameras, radar, lidar, and ultrasonic sensors, processing this information through artificial intelligence trained on millions of driving miles. Current systems handle highway driving and simple suburban routes impressively. However, edge cases‚Äîunusual situations not represented in training data‚Äîexpose dangerous limitations. A plastic bag floating across a road might be interpreted as an obstacle requiring emergency braking; unusual weather conditions can confuse sensors that learned primarily from sunny California drives. More troubling are ethical decisions programmed into these systems. If an accident is unavoidable, should the car prioritize passenger safety or minimize total harm? Should it swerve into one pedestrian to avoid hitting three? Human drivers make these decisions instinctively, without explicit moral calculation. Autonomous vehicles require programmers to decide in advance whose lives matter more in various scenarios. Legal frameworks lag behind technology. Liability when autonomous vehicles crash remains unclear. Insurance companies struggle to price risk for vehicles with no human driver. Employment disruption threatens millions of professional drivers. Despite challenges, autonomous technology continues advancing. Partial automation already makes driving safer, even if fully autonomous vehicles remain a distant destination.",
