                id: 190,
                title: "Earth's Mass Extinctions (R)",
                text: "Life on Earth has nearly ended five times. These mass extinctions, each eliminating more than seventy percent of species, punctuate the fossil record with sudden gaps. Understanding past extinctions provides sobering context for current biodiversity losses and human impacts on planetary systems. The largest extinction, 252 million years ago, killed approximately 96% of marine species and 70% of land vertebrates. Called the 'Great Dying,' it likely resulted from massive volcanic eruptions in present-day Siberia. These eruptions released greenhouse gases causing runaway warming, ocean acidification, and oxygen depletion in seas‚Äîconditions that took millions of years to stabilize. The most famous extinction, 66 million years ago, ended the dinosaurs' reign. An asteroid impact in present-day Mexico triggered immediate destruction, then prolonged nuclear winter as debris blocked sunlight. Yet this catastrophe enabled mammalian diversification, eventually producing humans. Each mass extinction reset evolution's direction. Species that dominated before became extinct; survivors radiated into vacated ecological niches. Life recovered each time, though recovery required millions of years. Today, extinction rates exceed background levels by one hundred to one thousand times. Unlike past events, current losses result from human activities: habitat destruction, pollution, climate change, and invasive species. Scientists debate whether we're witnessing the sixth mass extinction. Whatever the label, preventing continued biodiversity loss requires understanding that Earth's history offers no guarantee of recovery.",
