                text: "Priya had grown up code-switching so automatically she barely noticed. At school, she was 'Priya,' eating cafeteria pizza, discussing football, masking her accent. At home, she was 'Priyanka,' speaking Tamil, practicing classical dance, embracing traditions her friends would find strange. Neither version felt like a performance‚Äîbut neither felt complete. The crisis crystallized during college applications. An essay prompt asked her to describe her cultural background. Priya stared at the blank screen, realizing she'd never integrated her identities into a coherent narrative. Was she Indian-American, American-Indian, both, neither? Did hyphenated identities erase the distinct meanings on each side? Her grandmother's visit coincided with this questioning. Watching Priya agonize, her grandmother shared her own immigration story‚Äîthe losses, the adaptations, the reinvention required to build life in a new country. 'You think I'm fully Indian?' her grandmother laughed. 'I'm something new. Something that didn't exist before. You are too.' Priya began exploring what that meant. She joined cultural organizations at school, connecting with other first-generation students navigating similar territory. She wrote her essay about code-switching itself‚Äînot as deception but as multilingual fluency across cultural contexts. The college that admitted her cited that essay specifically. More importantly, Priya stopped seeing her dual identity as something to reconcile and started seeing it as something to celebrate‚Äîa unique vantage point observing two worlds from inside both.",
