                text: "In the summer of 1961, eighteen-year-old Dolores Garcia boarded a Greyhound bus in Washington, D.C., knowing she might not survive the journey. She was joining the Freedom Riders‚Äîinterracial groups challenging segregation in interstate travel despite Supreme Court rulings declaring it unconstitutional. The law was clear; the South's refusal to enforce it was equally clear. The first days passed tensely but without major incident. Then they crossed into Alabama. At Anniston, a mob surrounded the bus, slashing tires and throwing a firebomb through a window. Passengers escaped through flames while attackers beat them with pipes and clubs. Dolores suffered burns and a broken arm; several riders were hospitalized in critical condition. The violence made national headlines, which was exactly the point. Freedom Riders understood that dramatic confrontation would force federal intervention in ways that lawsuits and lobbying hadn't. Each beating, each arrest, each image of American citizens attacked for exercising legal rights eroded the moral legitimacy of segregation. Dolores continued riding through Mississippi, where police arrested passengers rather than protecting them from mobs. She spent weeks in Parchman Prison, subjected to conditions designed to break protesters' spirits. Instead, imprisonment strengthened her commitment. The Freedom Rides eventually succeeded. Interstate terminals desegregated under federal pressure. But Dolores never forgot that justice required ordinary people accepting extraordinary risks.",
