                text: "Few issues generate more passionate disagreement than immigration. Debates involve economics, culture, security, and fundamental questions about national identity and humanitarian obligations. Understanding multiple perspectives helps navigate a conversation too often dominated by simplistic slogans. Economic arguments appear on both sides. Immigration's advocates note that immigrants start businesses at higher rates than native-born citizens, fill crucial labor shortages, and contribute more in taxes than they consume in services over their lifetimes. Critics argue that low-skilled immigration depresses wages for native workers, particularly those without college degrees, and strains public services in receiving communities. Cultural concerns also divide opinion. Some see immigration as enriching societies through diverse perspectives, cuisines, and traditions. Others worry about social cohesion when newcomers don't assimilate, maintaining separate languages and customs that fragment national identity. Both perspectives contain legitimate insights that absolutist positions ignore. Security considerations have gained prominence. Terrorists have occasionally exploited immigration systems, though statistical risk from immigrants remains lower than from native-born citizens. The more significant security issue involves unauthorized immigration, which creates populations outside legal systems and can facilitate exploitation by employers and criminals. Humanitarian obligations complicate restrictive approaches. International law requires accepting refugees fleeing persecution. Climate change and economic instability will likely increase migration pressure globally. Simply closing borders doesn't eliminate push factors driving people to move‚Äîit merely determines whether migration occurs legally or not.",
