                title: "Growing Apart (T)",
                text: "At seven, Aiden and Simone were inseparable‚Äîfinishing each other's sentences, sharing secrets, defending each other against playground bullies. At seventeen, they could barely sustain conversation. The drift had been so gradual neither could identify when friendship became obligation. College applications forced confrontation. They'd always assumed they'd attend the same university, but Simone had quietly applied to schools across the country without telling Aiden. He discovered this accidentally, through a mutual friend's Instagram post congratulating her on an acceptance. Confronting her, Aiden expected denial or apology. Instead, Simone expressed relief that the secret was out. 'I've been pretending for years,' she admitted. 'Pretending our friendship is still what it was when we were kids. We don't actually have anything in common anymore. We just have history.' The words stung because they were true. Aiden's interests had diverged toward computer science and gaming; Simone had discovered political activism and journalism. Their conversations had become performances of friendship rather than genuine connection‚Äîreferencing shared memories instead of building new ones. Accepting the relationship's natural conclusion was painful but ultimately freeing. They stopped forcing interactions, stopped pretending mutual enthusiasm for each other's passions. Years later, they reconnected as adults with fully formed identities and discovered, unexpectedly, that they could build an adult friendship unburdened by childhood expectations. Sometimes relationships need endings before they can have new beginnings.",
