                id: 211,
                title: "Dust Bowl Diary (T)",
                text: "April 14, 1935. They call it Black Sunday. I watched the sky turn from clear blue to absolute darkness in minutes‚Äîa wall of dust two hundred feet high rolling toward us like God's judgment. Papa barely got the livestock sheltered before it hit. Even inside, sealed against every crack, the dust found us. It coated everything‚Äîour food, our water, our lungs. This is the fourth year of drought. The fifth of dust storms. Our wheat farm, which had prospered for twenty years, now grows nothing but poverty. The soil, plowed and planted without understanding consequences, simply blew away when rain stopped falling. We were told the land was inexhaustible. We were wrong. Mama stitched wet cloths over windows and doorframes, but still the children cough constantly. Baby Michael's lungs sound like rattling paper. The doctor says he's seen many cases of 'dust pneumonia'‚Äîa disease that didn't exist before we broke the prairie. We've eaten the last of our stored grain. Neighbors have already left for California, chasing rumors of work picking fruit. Papa refuses to abandon land his father homesteaded. But what is land worth when it's killing us? I'm seventeen years old. I've seen my future erode with every dust storm‚Äîthe education I'd hoped for, the life I'd imagined. Yet somehow we endure. Perhaps that stubborn persistence is both our greatest strength and our fatal flaw.",
