                id: 214,
                title: "Ocean Acidification (T)",
                text: "Climate change's most famous consequence is warming, but a less-publicized effect may prove equally destructive: the ocean is becoming more acidic. As atmospheric carbon dioxide levels rise, oceans absorb approximately 25% of emissions, triggering chemical changes that threaten marine ecosystems from microscopic plankton to coral reefs to commercial fisheries. When carbon dioxide dissolves in seawater, it forms carbonic acid. Since industrialization began, ocean acidity has increased approximately 30%‚Äîa rate of change unprecedented in at least 55 million years. Marine organisms that evolved in stable chemical conditions now face rapidly shifting environments. Shell-building organisms suffer most directly. Increased acidity reduces available carbonate ions that mollusks, corals, and certain plankton use to construct shells and skeletons. Experiments show that under projected future conditions, some organisms' shells literally dissolve. Coral reefs, already stressed by warming, face additional assault on their calcium carbonate structures. The implications cascade through food webs. Pteropods‚Äîtiny swimming snails sometimes called 'sea butterflies'‚Äîform the base of many ocean food chains. Their decline would affect fish populations that depend on them, eventually impacting commercial fisheries and communities relying on seafood. Some adaptation may occur. Certain species demonstrate capacity to adjust to acidification over generations. However, current rates of change likely exceed many organisms' adaptive capabilities. Even optimistic emissions scenarios suggest significant ecosystem disruption, while continued high emissions could render many ocean environments inhospitable to calcifying organisms entirely.",
