                id: 217,
                title: "Mental Health Stigma (T)",
                text: "Despite affecting approximately one in five adults annually, mental illness remains surrounded by stigma that prevents millions from seeking treatment. Understanding stigma's origins and effects helps explain why mental health care lags so far behind physical health care in accessibility and acceptance. Stigma operates at multiple levels. Public stigma involves negative attitudes society holds toward mental illness‚Äîstereotypes of dangerousness, weakness, or unpredictability. Self-stigma occurs when individuals internalize these attitudes, feeling shame about their conditions. Structural stigma appears in policies and practices that disadvantage people with mental illness, from insurance limitations to employment discrimination. Historical context shaped current attitudes. Mental illness was long attributed to demonic possession, moral failing, or character weakness. Even after medical understanding improved, institutionalization in often-abusive facilities reinforced associations between mental illness and social exclusion. Media portrayals linking mental illness with violence‚Äîdespite evidence that mentally ill individuals are more likely to be crime victims than perpetrators‚Äîperpetuate harmful stereotypes. Stigma has measurable consequences. Approximately 60% of adults with diagnosable mental illness receive no treatment in a given year. Many avoid seeking help due to fear of judgment from employers, family, or friends. Delayed treatment typically worsens outcomes‚Äîearly intervention in conditions like schizophrenia or depression dramatically improves prognosis. Reducing stigma requires multiple approaches: education countering misconceptions, contact with individuals living successfully with mental illness, language changes that separate people from their diagnoses, and policy reforms ensuring equal treatment coverage.",
