                id: 220,
                title: "The Apology (U)",
                text: "Twenty years after high school, Marcus Chen received an email that reopened wounds he'd thought healed. The sender was Brendan Walker‚Äîthe person who had made Marcus's adolescence miserable through relentless bullying. Brendan was in Marcus's city, wanted to meet, and wanted to apologize. Marcus's immediate reaction was refusal. Why should he provide closure to someone who had caused such damage? The bullying had affected his self-esteem well into adulthood, contributed to social anxiety, shaped how he interacted with others. Brendan had no right to absolution now, decades later. But curiosity‚Äîand perhaps hope‚Äîeventually prevailed. They met at a coffee shop, neutral territory. Brendan was unrecognizable: heavier, graying, none of the predatory confidence Marcus remembered. He didn't make excuses. He described his home life during those years‚Äîan abusive father, his own daily terror‚Äînot as justification but as context. He acknowledged that passing his pain to Marcus was inexcusable regardless of reasons. 'I'm not asking you to forgive me,' Brendan said. 'I'm asking you to know that I understand what I did. That I've thought about it for years. That I'm genuinely sorry.' Marcus wasn't sure what he felt. Not forgiveness exactly, but something released. The apology didn't undo the past, but it changed its meaning somehow. Brendan had been a monster in Marcus's memory; now he was a damaged person who had caused damage‚Äîcomprehensible, even pitiable. Marcus left the meeting feeling lighter, though he couldn't precisely explain why.",
