                text: "Dr. Sarah Chen's invention was supposed to be a forecasting tool‚Äîpredicting weather, stock markets, traffic patterns. The Probability Engine modeled complex systems with unprecedented accuracy, extrapolating likely futures from current conditions. She never anticipated it would show her the moment of her own death. The malfunction occurred during routine testing. Instead of economic projections, the screen displayed a probability tree for Sarah's personal timeline. One branch, glowing ominous red, showed a fatal car accident at a specific intersection, three months from now, with 94.7% probability. The other branches showed longer lives, but all converged eventually‚Äîas all lives must. Her first impulse was dismissal. The engine wasn't designed for biological prediction; the result was meaningless noise. But the same mathematics that accurately forecast hurricane paths and market crashes underpinned this prediction. Either her life's work was valid or it wasn't. Sarah became obsessed with the intersection: a routine part of her daily commute. She altered her route, but the probability adjusted‚Äîdifferent intersection, similar outcome. She stopped driving entirely; the probability shifted to pedestrian accidents. The engine modeled her responses, incorporating them into new forecasts. Eventually, she realized the trap. Living to avoid predicted death wasn't living at all. She shut down the probability engine, returned to her normal routine, and accepted that uncertainty was preferable to predicted certainty. The three-month deadline passed without incident. She never determined whether the prediction had been wrong or whether her acceptance had somehow altered the outcome.",
