                id: 230,
                title: "Cold Case (V)",
                text: "The disappearance of Margaret Holloway in 1978 had remained Clearwater County's most persistent mystery for forty-three years when journalism student Kenji Watanabe began investigating for his senior thesis. Margaret, then twenty-two, vanished after leaving her night shift at the local hospital. Her car was found abandoned on a rural road; she was never seen again. Previous investigations had generated theories but no answers. Some suspected her estranged husband; others blamed a serial killer active in neighboring counties. Without a body or clear evidence, the case went cold. Kenji approached the investigation differently. He digitized all available records, using computational analysis to identify inconsistencies police had missed. He tracked down witnesses now elderly, collecting memories before they were lost forever. He built timelines cross-referenced with weather records, shift schedules, and traffic patterns. Gradually, patterns emerged. Multiple witnesses reported seeing Margaret's car‚Äînot abandoned but driven‚Äîheading toward the county's industrial district. Her husband had an alibi, but his brother did not. Financial records showed the brother had unexpectedly paid off debts soon after Margaret's disappearance. Most damningly, the brother had purchased property along the very road where Margaret's car was found. Kenji presented his findings to the district attorney, who authorized excavation of the property. They found Margaret's remains, along with personal effects that confirmed her identity. The brother, now seventy-four, was arrested for murder. Justice, Kenji reflected, sometimes required decades‚Äîand someone willing to look when others had given up.",
