                id: 232,
                title: "The Reunion (V)",
                text: "Fifteen years after their friendship imploded, Naomi received a wedding invitation from Danielle‚Äîthe person she'd once considered her soulmate, before everything went wrong. The invitation came with a handwritten note: 'I know this is unexpected. I'm getting married, I'm finally happy, and I realized I can't fully move forward without acknowledging the past. Will you come?' Their rupture had been spectacular. They'd been graduate students, roommates, inseparable since college. Then Naomi discovered Danielle had been secretly dating her ex-boyfriend‚Äîhad been, in fact, the reason for their breakup. The betrayal felt like losing two people at once. For years afterward, Naomi found herself unable to trust fully, always waiting for friends to reveal hidden agendas. She'd built a satisfying life despite this‚Äîcareer, partner, children‚Äîbut something remained unresolved. The wedding was in Danielle's hometown, across the country. Attending meant confronting pain Naomi had worked hard to bury. Not attending meant carrying that unfinished business forever. She went. The reunion was awkward at first‚Äîstilted small talk, careful avoidance of loaded topics. Then Danielle asked if they could speak privately. She didn't make excuses. She acknowledged her betrayal fully, took responsibility without qualification, expressed regret that seemed genuine. 'I was selfish and cowardly. You deserved better.' Forgiveness didn't happen instantly, but something shifted. Naomi realized she'd been carrying anger that served no purpose, protecting against a threat that no longer existed. She couldn't recover the lost friendship, but she could release the weight of resentment. Sometimes closure comes from the most unexpected places.",
