                id: 238,
                title: "Climate Refugees (V)",
                text: "The village of Shishmaref, Alaska, has existed on its barrier island for over 4,000 years. Now, rising sea levels and coastal erosion threaten to eliminate it within decades. Its residents face a decision confronting growing numbers worldwide: relocate or watch their homes disappear. They are among the world's first climate refugees. The term remains contested‚Äîcurrent international law doesn't recognize climate change as grounds for refugee status. Yet by 2050, an estimated 200 million people may be displaced by rising seas, intensifying storms, drought, and other climate impacts. Most will move within their own countries; many will cross borders seeking survival. Pacific island nations face existential threats. Kiribati, where much of the land sits barely above sea level, has purchased property in Fiji as potential refuge. The Maldives' entire economy depends on beaches that may not exist in thirty years. These nations bear minimal responsibility for climate change yet suffer its most severe consequences. Climate migration already reshapes demographics. Prolonged drought drove millions of Syrian farmers into cities before the civil war‚Äîa migration scholars argue destabilized the nation. Central American agricultural failures push migrants northward toward the United States. Bangladesh loses coastal land to flooding while its population grows, creating density pressures that cannot be sustainably resolved domestically. Policy responses remain inadequate. International frameworks for climate migration don't exist. Host communities fear being overwhelmed by arrivals. Source communities lose their most capable members. Adapting to climate-driven population movements may prove as challenging as addressing climate change itself.",
