                id: 239,
                title: "The Vietnam War: America's Longest Conflict (V)",
                text: "For twenty years, from 1955 to 1975, the United States engaged in Vietnam‚Äîfirst advising, then fighting, ultimately withdrawing in defeat. This conflict killed over 58,000 Americans and an estimated 2 million Vietnamese, divided American society more deeply than any event since the Civil War, and permanently altered how Americans view military intervention abroad. The war's origins lay in colonialism and Cold War ideology. France's attempt to reassert colonial control after World War II collapsed at Dien Bien Phu in 1954. Fearing communist expansion, the United States supported South Vietnam's government against communist North Vietnam and its southern guerrilla allies, the Viet Cong. American involvement escalated gradually. Military advisors became combat troops; limited engagement became total war. By 1968, over 500,000 American soldiers were deployed. Despite overwhelming firepower, victory proved elusive against an enemy fighting on home terrain for national unification. The war transformed American politics. The draft made military service unavoidable for many families, broadening opposition beyond pacifists. Television brought combat into living rooms, undermining optimistic official narratives. The credibility gap‚Äîdisconnect between government claims and observable reality‚Äîbred lasting distrust of authority. Vietnam's lessons remain contested. Some argue that military restraint prevented victory; others contend the war was unwinnable regardless. The conflict demonstrated limits of technological superiority against determined adversaries and revealed democratic governments' difficulty sustaining unpopular wars. These lessons informed‚Äîor were ignored in‚Äîsubsequent American interventions.",
