                id: 240,
                title: "Esports: Gaming Goes Professional (V)",
                text: "In 2019, a sixteen-year-old named Kyle Giersdorf won $3 million playing Fortnite. His victory at the World Cup Finals, watched by millions online, exemplified competitive gaming's transformation from hobbyist pastime to professional sport commanding massive audiences and revenues. Esports' growth has been exponential. Global revenues exceed $1 billion annually. Major tournaments fill stadiums that host traditional sports; the 2018 League of Legends World Championship drew over 99 million unique viewers. Investment from traditional sports franchises, entertainment companies, and venture capital has legitimized what was once dismissed as adolescent recreation. The ecosystem mirrors traditional sports in many ways. Professional players sign contracts, practice full-time, and compete on salaried teams with coaches, analysts, and support staff. College esports programs offer scholarships. Careers, however, tend to be brief‚Äîreaction times peak in the early twenties, making retirement by thirty common. Physical and mental health concerns have emerged. Professional gamers report repetitive strain injuries, vision problems, and burnout from training regimens exceeding twelve hours daily. Unlike traditional athletes, they lack the physical exercise that might counterbalance sedentary competition. Some organizations now mandate physical fitness programs and limit practice hours. Debates about esports' legitimacy continue. Critics question whether gaming deserves classification alongside activities requiring physical prowess. Proponents note that chess is recognized as a sport despite similar characteristics. As esports' cultural footprint expands, definitions of athletic competition may simply need updating.",
