                id: 241,
                title: "Money in Politics (V)",
                text: "The 2020 U.S. election cycle saw over $14 billion in campaign spending‚Äîmore than the gross domestic product of some nations. This flood of money into democratic processes raises fundamental questions about political equality: Can elections be fair when wealthy interests dominate campaign funding? Does contribution equal speech, or does it corrupt representation? The American system permits enormous political spending following legal developments culminating in the Supreme Court's 2010 Citizens United decision. That ruling held that political spending by corporations and unions constitutes protected speech that cannot be limited. Subsequent decisions removed most remaining restrictions, enabling unlimited contributions to groups supporting candidates without directly coordinating with campaigns. Proponents argue that spending enhances political discourse, allowing ideas to reach broader audiences. In this view, restricting expenditures restricts expression‚Äîan unacceptable limit on First Amendment freedoms. If people want to pool resources supporting candidates, government shouldn't prevent them. Critics counter that unrestricted money amplifies wealthy voices at ordinary citizens' expense. When billionaires can fund entire campaigns while average donors contribute hundreds of dollars, mathematical equality of voting means little. Politicians spending increasing time fundraising inevitably become more attentive to donors' concerns. The corruption may be subtle‚Äîrarely explicit quid pro quo, more often shifting priorities and access patterns. International comparisons suggest alternatives. Many democracies limit campaign spending, provide public financing, or restrict contribution sources. These systems remain democratic while reducing money's distorting influence. Whether American democracy can adapt remains an open question.",
