                id: 242,
                title: "The Algorithm (W)",
                text: "When the behavioral prediction algorithm identified seventeen-year-old Marcus Thompson as having a 94% probability of committing a violent crime within the next year, his life changed instantly. He hadn't done anything‚Äîthe algorithm processed social media activity, academic records, neighborhood demographics, and hundreds of other variables to generate its assessment. Yet based solely on this prediction, Marcus found himself excluded from college programs, flagged for additional police surveillance, and viewed with suspicion by neighbors who'd known him since childhood. Marcus became a test case for algorithmic accountability. Civil liberties attorneys took his case, arguing that punishing individuals for crimes they haven't committed‚Äîand might never commit‚Äîviolated fundamental principles of justice. The algorithm's developers countered that their system had prevented dozens of violent incidents; some collateral unfairness was acceptable given lives saved. The technical defense was equally disturbing. The algorithm was a black box: even its creators couldn't fully explain why it flagged specific individuals. Machine learning had identified patterns in historical data, but these patterns reflected existing biases‚Äîoverpolicing of minority neighborhoods, for instance, created data suggesting minorities were more criminal. The algorithm learned and amplified human prejudices while appearing objective. Marcus's case eventually reached the Supreme Court, which ruled that algorithmic predictions couldn't justify preemptive restrictions on liberty without human oversight and explainable reasoning. The ruling didn't solve the underlying problem‚Äîalgorithms continued operating in less visible contexts‚Äîbut it established that efficiency couldn't wholly replace justice.",
