                id: 250,
                title: "The Sixth Extinction (W)",
                text: "Earth has experienced five mass extinction events, each eliminating the majority of species then living. Growing scientific consensus holds that human activity is triggering a sixth extinction, with current species loss rates exceeding background levels by one hundred to one thousand times. Whether this process can be slowed‚Äîlet alone reversed‚Äîremains uncertain. Unlike previous extinction events caused by asteroid impacts or volcanic eruptions, the current crisis stems from a single species' activities. Habitat destruction eliminates the environments species need to survive. Overexploitation directly removes individuals faster than populations can recover. Pollution contaminates ecosystems with substances organisms never evolved to tolerate. Introduced species outcompete natives evolved in their absence. Climate change alters conditions faster than most species can adapt. The evidence is overwhelming. Vertebrate populations have declined approximately 68% since 1970. Insect populations show similar patterns, threatening pollination and food chains. Coral reefs are projected to decline 70-90% with 1.5¬∞C warming. The Amazon approaches tipping points beyond which rainforest transitions to savanna. Ecosystem services‚Äîpollination, water purification, carbon sequestration, disease regulation‚Äîdepend on biodiversity that is rapidly disappearing. Economic analyses value these services at trillions of dollars annually. Yet market systems largely fail to price biodiversity's value, creating incentives for destruction rather than preservation. Conservation efforts have achieved notable successes: species brought back from extinction's edge, habitats protected and restored, international agreements coordinating conservation action. Whether these efforts can scale to match the crisis's magnitude‚Äîor whether humanity will witness, and cause, a mass extinction in real time‚Äîremains the defining environmental question of our era.",
