                id: 255,
                title: "Space Station Emergency (X)",
                text: "The micrometeorite strike was too small to trigger automated alarms but large enough to puncture the International Space Station's hull. Commander Elena Rodriguez noticed the pressure differential before warning systems activated‚Äîher years of experience had developed sensitivity to the station's normal sounds, and something was wrong. She traced the breach to the Zarya module, where air whistled through a hole smaller than a pencil eraser. The crew had practiced this scenario countless times, but training simulations couldn't replicate the primal fear of atmosphere escaping into vacuum. They had perhaps thirty minutes before the module became uninhabitable. Standard procedure called for sealing the compromised module, but Zarya contained critical life support equipment‚Äîisolating it would create cascading problems throughout the station. Elena made a different call: attempt repair while maintaining habitation. The repair kit contained specialized patches designed for exactly this situation, but applying them required steady hands in a deteriorating environment. Elena worked while crew members monitored pressure, ready to evacuate if readings dropped below survivable thresholds. The patch held. Pressure stabilized. The station's integrity was restored through skill, preparation, and calm decision-making under conditions that would have induced panic in most people. Elena's report to ground control was matter-of-fact; the crisis had been managed according to protocols that existed for precisely such emergencies. But that night, alone in her sleeping quarters, she permitted herself to acknowledge the terror she had suppressed while lives depended on her clarity. Space was unforgiving; humans survived there only through competence maintained against relentless hostility.",
