                id: 271,
                title: "Tiananmen Square (Y)",
                text: "Beijing, June 1989. Twenty-year-old Wei had been protesting in Tiananmen Square for seven weeks. What began as mourning for reformist leader Hu Yaobang had become the largest pro-democracy movement in Chinese history. Hundreds of thousands occupied the square, demanding political liberalization, freedom of expression, and government accountability. Wei, a university student studying literature, had found purpose she had never known existed. The atmosphere was intoxicating‚Äîstudents debating philosophy, workers joining their cause, international media broadcasting their movement worldwide. When student leaders erected the 'Goddess of Democracy' statue facing Mao's portrait, Wei felt history turning. They were changing China. Rumors of military action circulated but seemed impossible. The People's Liberation Army existed to protect the people; surely soldiers wouldn't fire on students. Even as troops massed outside Beijing, protesters believed moral righteousness would protect them. Wei's parents begged her to leave; she refused, convinced that abandoning the square meant betraying everything they had fought for. The military assault on June 3rd and 4th shattered those beliefs. Wei witnessed tanks advancing through barricades, heard automatic weapons firing into crowds, saw friends fall and not rise. She escaped through back streets while the square was cleared, emerging into a city transformed by terror. The protests were crushed. In the following weeks, leaders were arrested, participants were identified and punished, and the movement was erased from official memory. Wei eventually fled China, carrying survivor's guilt and determination that the world would remember what her government wanted forgotten. Thirty years later, she still observes the anniversary, lighting candles for classmates who never grew old.",
