                id: 273,
                title: "Genetic Engineering Ethics: Should We Design Our Children? (Y)",
                text: "Preimplantation genetic testing already allows parents to select embryos free from serious genetic diseases. As technology advances, selection could extend to traits like height, intelligence, or appearance. Eventually, direct genetic modification might enable designing children to specification. These possibilities raise profound ethical questions about human reproduction and the nature of parenthood. Arguments for genetic enhancement emphasize benefits to future children. Eliminating hereditary diseases prevents suffering. Enhancing capabilities‚Äîcognitive, physical, psychological‚Äîcould improve quality of life. Parents already shape children's environments to promote development; why should genetic influences be different? If enhancement becomes possible, denying it might itself constitute harm by condemning children to limitations that could have been prevented. Counterarguments emphasize risks and values concerns. Genetic intervention could have unpredictable consequences given our incomplete understanding of how genes interact. Enhancement could exacerbate inequality‚Äîif available only to wealthy families, genetic modification might create permanent biological class distinctions. The commodification of children as products designed to parental specification fundamentally alters reproductive relationships. Disability rights advocates argue that genetic selection devalues people living with conditions deemed undesirable. The line between treatment and enhancement proves philosophically slippery. Selecting against Huntington's disease seems clearly therapeutic, but what about selecting for higher intelligence? Genetic conditions exist on spectrums; where does disease end and normal variation begin? These questions implicate fundamental values about human diversity, parental obligations, and what children are owed by the societies that produce them. Governance frameworks must balance precautionary principles against potential benefits, navigating between restriction that blocks genuine improvements and permissiveness that enables harm. International coordination is essential given that prohibitions in one jurisdiction may simply redirect activity elsewhere.",
