                title: "The Rwandan Genocide: Survivors' Stories (Z)",
                text: "In one hundred days in 1994, approximately 800,000 people‚Äîmainly ethnic Tutsis‚Äîwere murdered in Rwanda. The genocide was executed primarily through machetes, making it horrifyingly intimate: neighbors killing neighbors, teachers killing students, husbands killing wives. Understanding this catastrophe requires engaging with survivor testimonies that convey both genocide's systematic nature and its irreducibly personal devastation. Immacul√©e Ilibagiza survived by hiding in a bathroom with seven other women for ninety-one days while killers searched her village. She could hear them discussing how they would murder her if found. Through those months of terror, she struggled with faith‚Äîhow could God permit such evil?‚Äîand eventually found spiritual resources that enabled her to survive psychologically as well as physically. Her memoir, Left to Tell, became an internationally recognized account of survival and forgiveness. Jean-Paul Samputu lost his parents and siblings to genocide, then discovered that his best friend had led the killers to his family. Years later, after the friend's imprisonment, Samputu chose to visit him, beginning a reconciliation process that eventually led to public forgiveness ceremonies. His story illustrates both genocide's social devastation‚Äîbetrayal by trusted intimates‚Äîand the complicated processes through which survivors have sought to rebuild individual relationships and national cohesion. Rwanda's post-genocide recovery has been remarkable and controversial. The government has emphasized national unity over ethnic identification, pursued economic development that has improved material conditions, and implemented community justice processes called gacaca courts. Critics argue that reconciliation has been imposed rather than genuine, that political repression accompanies economic progress, and that underlying tensions remain unresolved. Survivors' perspectives on recovery vary enormously‚Äîsome finding meaning through forgiveness, others maintaining that certain crimes deserve permanent condemnation.",
